#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:259
#, no-c-format
msgid "Writing Shell Scripts"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: primary
#: adm_shell.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid "Shell scripts"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:263
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Shell scripts are a convenient way of doing all sorts of tasks: collecting "
"data, searching for a word or phrase in a text and many other useful things. "
"The following example shows a small shell script that prints a text:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:270
#, no-c-format
msgid "A Shell Script Printing a Text"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:271
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"#!/bin/sh <co xml:id=\"co.adm.shell.shebang\"/>\n"
"# Output the following line: <co xml:id=\"co.adm.shell.comment\"/>\n"
"echo \"Hello World\" <co xml:id=\"co.adm.shell.echo\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:274
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The first line begins with the <emphasis>Shebang</emphasis> <indexterm> "
"<primary>Shebang</primary> </indexterm> characters (<literal>#!</literal>) "
"which is an indicator that this file is a script. The script is executed "
"with the specified interpreter after the Shebang, in this case <command>/bin/"
"sh</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The second line is a comment beginning with the hash sign. It is recommended "
"to comment difficult lines to remember what they do."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:289
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The third line uses the built-in command <command>echo</command> to print "
"the corresponding text."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "Before you can run this script you need some prerequisites:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:303
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Every script should contain a Shebang line (this is already the case with "
"our example above.) If a script does not have this line, you need to call "
"the interpreter manually."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can save the script wherever you want. However, it is a good idea to "
"save it in a directory where the shell can find it. The search path in a "
"shell is determined by the environment variable <envar>PATH</envar>. Usually "
"a normal user does not have write access to <filename>/usr/bin</filename>. "
"Therefore it is recommended to save your scripts in the users' directory "
"<filename>~/bin/</filename>. The above example gets the name <filename>hello."
"sh</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The script needs executable permissions. Set the permissions with the "
"following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:325
#, no-c-format
msgid "chmod +x ~/bin/hello.sh"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:329
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you have fulfilled all of the above prerequisites, you can execute the "
"script in the following ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:337
#, no-c-format
msgid "As Absolute Path"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:338
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The script can be executed with an absolute path. In our case, it is "
"<command>~/bin/hello.sh</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:346
#, no-c-format
msgid "Everywhere"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:347
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the <envar>PATH</envar> environment variable contains the directory where "
"the script is located, you can execute the script with <command>hello.sh</"
"command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:357
#, no-c-format
msgid "Redirecting Command Events"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:359
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each command can use three channels, either for input or output:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:366
#, no-c-format
msgid "Standard Output"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:367
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This is the default output channel. Whenever a command prints something, it "
"uses the standard output channel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:375
#, no-c-format
msgid "Standard Input"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:376
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If a command needs input from users or other commands, it uses this channel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:384
#, no-c-format
msgid "Standard Error"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:385
#, no-c-format
msgid "Commands use this channel for error reporting."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:392
#, no-c-format
msgid "To redirect these channels, there are the following possibilities:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:398
#, no-c-format
msgid "Command &gt; File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:401
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Saves the output of the command into a file, an existing file will be "
"deleted. For example, the <command>ls</command> command writes its output "
"into the file <filename>listing.txt</filename>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:406
#, no-c-format
msgid "ls &gt; listing.txt"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:410
#, no-c-format
msgid "Command &gt;&gt; File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:413
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Appends the output of the command to a file. For example, the <command>ls</"
"command> command appends its output to the file <filename>listing.txt</"
"filename>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:418
#, no-c-format
msgid "ls &gt;&gt; listing.txt"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:422
#, no-c-format
msgid "Command &lt; File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Reads the file as input for the given command. For example, the "
"<command>read</command> command reads in the content of the file into the "
"variable:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:430
#, no-c-format
msgid "read a &lt; foo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:434
#, no-c-format
msgid "Command1 | Command2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:437
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Redirects the output of the left command as input for the right command. For "
"example, the <command>cat</command> command outputs the content of the "
"<filename>/proc/cpuinfo</filename> file. This output is used by "
"<command>grep</command> to filter only those lines which contain "
"<literal>cpu</literal>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:444
#, no-c-format
msgid "cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep cpu"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:449
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Every channel has a <emphasis>file descriptor</emphasis>: 0 (zero) for "
"standard input, 1 for standard output and 2 for standard error. It is "
"allowed to insert this file descriptor before a <literal>&lt;</literal> or "
"<literal>&gt;</literal> character. For example, the following line searches "
"for a file starting with <filename>foo</filename>, but suppresses its errors "
"by redirecting it to <filename>/dev/null</filename>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:458
#, no-c-format
msgid "find / -name \"foo*\" 2&gt;/dev/null"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:461
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Aliases"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: primary
#: adm_shell.xml:463
#, no-c-format
msgid "aliases"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:465
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An alias is a shortcut definition of one or more commands. The syntax for an "
"alias is:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:470
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"alias <replaceable>NAME</replaceable>=<replaceable>DEFINITION</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:472
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, the following line defines an alias <command>lt</command> which "
"outputs a long listing (option <option>-l</option>), sorts it by "
"modification time (<option>-t</option>) and prints it in reverse order while "
"sorting (<option>-r</option>):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:479
#, no-c-format
msgid "alias lt='ls -ltr'"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:481
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To view all alias definitions, use <command>alias</command>. Remove your "
"alias with <command>unalias</command> and the corresponding alias name."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:487
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Variables in Bash"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A shell variable can be global or local. Global variables, or environment "
"variables, can be accessed in all shells. In contrast, local variables are "
"visible in the current shell only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:495
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To view all environment variables, use the <command>printenv</command> "
"command. If you need to know the value of a variable, insert the name of "
"your variable as an argument:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "printenv PATH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:503
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A variable, be it global or local, can also be viewed with <command>echo</"
"command>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:508
#, no-c-format
msgid "echo $PATH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:510
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To set a local variable, use a variable name followed by the equal sign, "
"followed by the value:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:515
#, no-c-format
msgid "PROJECT=\"SLED\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:517
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Do not insert spaces around the equal sign, otherwise you get an error. To "
"set an environment variable, use <command>export</command>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:522
#, no-c-format
msgid "export NAME=\"tux\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:524
#, no-c-format
msgid "To remove a variable, use <command>unset</command>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:528
#, no-c-format
msgid "unset NAME"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:530
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following table contains some common environment variables which can be "
"used in you shell scripts:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid "Useful Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid "HOME"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:546
#, no-c-format
msgid "the home directory of the current user"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:554
#, no-c-format
msgid "HOST"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid "the current host name"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "LANG"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:570
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"when a tool is localized, it uses the language from this environment "
"variable. English can also be set to <literal>C</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:579
#, no-c-format
msgid "PATH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:583
#, no-c-format
msgid "the search path of the shell, a list of directories separated by colon"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:591
#, no-c-format
msgid "<envar>PS1</envar>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:595
#, no-c-format
msgid "specifies the normal prompt printed before each command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "<envar>PS2</envar>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:607
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"specifies the secondary prompt printed when you execute a multi-line command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:616
#, no-c-format
msgid "<envar>PWD</envar>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:620
#, no-c-format
msgid "current working directory"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: envar
#: adm_shell.xml:628
#, no-c-format
msgid "USER"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:632
#, no-c-format
msgid "the current user"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:642
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Argument Variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:649
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, if you have the script <command>foo.sh</command> you can "
"execute it like this:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:653
#, no-c-format
msgid "foo.sh \"Tux Penguin\" 2000"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:654
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To access all the arguments which are passed to your script, you need "
"positional parameters. These are <envar>$1</envar> for the first argument, "
"<envar>$2</envar> for the second, and so on. You can have up to nine "
"parameters. To get the script name, use <envar>$0</envar>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following script <command>foo.sh</command> prints all arguments from 1 "
"to 4:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:664
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"#!/bin/sh\n"
"echo \\\"$1\\\" \\\"$2\\\" \\\"$3\\\" \\\"$4\\\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:665
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you execute this script with the above arguments, you get:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:668
#, no-c-format
msgid "\"Tux Penguin\" \"2000\" \"\" \"\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using Variable Substitution"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:733
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Variable substitutions apply a pattern to the content of a variable either "
"from the left or right side. The following list contains the possible syntax "
"forms:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:740
#, no-c-format
msgid "${VAR#pattern}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:743
#, no-c-format
msgid "removes the shortest possible match from the left:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:746
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"file=/home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2\n"
"echo ${file#*/}\n"
"home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:750
#, no-c-format
msgid "${VAR##pattern}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:753
#, no-c-format
msgid "removes the longest possible match from the left:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:756
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"file=/home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2\n"
"echo ${file##*/}\n"
"book.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:760
#, no-c-format
msgid "${VAR%pattern}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:763
#, no-c-format
msgid "removes the shortest possible match from the right:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:766
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"file=/home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2\n"
"echo ${file%.*}\n"
"/home/tux/book/book.tar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:770
#, no-c-format
msgid "${VAR%%pattern}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:773
#, no-c-format
msgid "removes the longest possible match from the right:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:776
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"file=/home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2\n"
"echo ${file%%.*}\n"
"/home/tux/book/book"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:780
#, no-c-format
msgid "${VAR/pattern_1/pattern_2}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:783
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"substitutes the content of <replaceable>VAR</replaceable> from the "
"<replaceable>pattern_1</replaceable> with <replaceable>pattern_2</"
"replaceable>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_shell.xml:788
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"file=/home/tux/book/book.tar.bz2\n"
"echo ${file/tux/wilber}\n"
"/home/wilber/book/book.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_shell.xml:808
#, no-c-format
msgid "Grouping and Combining Commands"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:810
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Shells allow you to concatenate and group commands for conditional "
"execution. Each command returns an exit code which determines the success or "
"failure of its operation. If it is 0 (zero) the command was successful, "
"everything else marks an error which is specific to the command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:817
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following list shows, how commands can be grouped:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_shell.xml:823
#, no-c-format
msgid "Command1 ; Command2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_shell.xml:826
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"executes the commands in sequential order. The exit code is not checked. The "
"following line displays the content of the file with <command>cat</command> "
"and then prints its file properties with <command>ls</command> regardless of "
"their exit codes:"
